Karnaphuli River Estuary Pollution Assessment Using Remote Sensing and Machine Learning
Overview
This research investigates water quality degradation in the Karnaphuli River Estuary, one of Bangladesh's most commercially significant and environmentally stressed waterways. Located near Chittagong, the estuary faces mounting pressure from industrial discharge, shipbreaking operations, and urban runoff, making it a critical site for pollution monitoring.
The study integrates laboratory water sampling, Sentinel-2A satellite imagery, and machine learning regression models to evaluate and spatially map physicochemical and heavy metal pollution across the estuary demonstrating a scalable, cost-effective framework for water quality monitoring in data-scarce environments.
Methodology
Collected 50 georeferenced water samples across the estuary and analyzed them for 14 heavy metals (including Aluminum and Iron) and 5 physicochemical parameters (pH, EC, TDS, TSS, and turbidity)
Acquired and processed Sentinel-2A Level-2A imagery via Google Earth Engine (GEE) and extracted spectral reflectance values at sampling locations using SNAP software
Trained and compared five machine learning regression models — Multiple Linear Regression, Ridge, Lasso, Support Vector Regression, and Principal Component Regression — using 10-fold cross-validation in Python (Google Colab)
Generated GIS-based Kriging interpolation maps to visualize spatial pollutant distribution and identify contamination hotspots near shipbreaking zones
Tools & Technologies
Python · Scikit-learn · Google Earth Engine · SNAP · GIS / Kriging · Sentinel-2A · Google Colab · Pandas · NumPy
Key Findings
Heavy metal concentrations, particularly Aluminum (up to 12.8 mg/L) and Iron (up to 15.5 mg/L) exceeded safe thresholds in samples collected near the industrialized coastal zone, with pollution hotspots most pronounced around the shipbreaking area. Sentinel-2A spectral bands demonstrated significant predictive value for optically active parameters such as turbidity and TSS, validating freely available satellite data as a viable monitoring tool for estuarine environments.
Significance
Traditional water quality monitoring is expensive, labor-intensive, and spatially limited. This study demonstrates that combining open-access satellite data with machine learning enables continuous, synoptic coverage of pollution levels offering a practical and replicable monitoring framework for riverine and estuarine systems across Bangladesh and similar data-scarce regions.
